  <body>
    <p>A 52-year-old woman presented with a small midline anterior neck mass and a 3-kg-weight loss over the course of one month. The patient was diagnosed with Graves disease based on increased free T4 levels (3.30 ng/dL), suppressed thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) levels (&lt;0.001 IU/mL), and a high titer of TSH receptor antibodies (32.6 IU/L). Scintigraphy with Tc-99m pertechnetate (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">Fig. 1</xref>) also revealed a diffusely enlarged thyroid gland with homogenous uptake, suggesting diffuse toxic goiter. Another uptake focus was noted apart from the pyramidal lobe, raising the possibility of ectopic thyroid tissue. Sonography of the thyroid gland (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="F2">Fig. 2</xref>) showed a 5.1&#xD7;10.1&#xD7;16.1 mm-sized isoechoic solid nodule within the thyroglossal duct, which would have enlarged as a result of hyperthyroidism. The cytology specimen of this nodule, which was obtained by fine needle aspiration, showed benign follicular cells. The patient is now being treated with 20 mg of methimazole.</p>
    <p>Thyroglossal duct remnants are the most common midline neck masses found during childhood, representing more than 75% of such masses [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1">1</xref>]. Approximately 7% of the adult population still has these remnants [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B2">2</xref>]. The presence of a solid mass along the thyroglossal duct cyst should raise the suspicion of ectopic thyroid tissue, as it is estimated that 35-70% may contain thyroid tissue in their wall [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B3">3</xref>]. Carcinoma arising from thyroglossal duct cysts is rare (only 1% of thyroglossal duct cases) and approximately 85-92% of all thyroglossal duct cyst carcinomas are papillary carcinomas [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B4">4</xref>]. Although they are characterized by relatively non-aggressive behavior and rare lymphatic spread [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B5">5</xref>], the possibility of occult malignancy should be evaluated in such cases.</p>
